{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "I propose in this text a rhythmic theory of signs drawn from the thought of Gilles Deleuze and Félix Guattari.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "I suggest that the theory of rhythm developed in A Thousand Plateaus (1980) can be understood, in part, as the culmination of the diverse set of inquiries into signs that both Deleuze and Guattari undertook, individually and together, beginning in the 1960s.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "I hope to evoke something of the character of the complex assemblage that is «Deleuze-Guattari», while suggesting that their theory of rhythm could provide a distinctive, heterodox contribution to semiotics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "What could these two profound critics of representation have to say about the exemplary representational notion that is the sign?",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Deleuze starts Proust and Signs with a rejection of a common opinion: the «search» of Proust's In Search of Lost Time is not, says Deleuze, a matter of recollection, of the involuntary memory with which Proust is most associated, but rather what Deleuze calls an «apprenticeship».",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Learning, undergoing the apprenticeship in signs, is then a process of interpretation and explication, of rethinking and renewing how one perceives, understands, and engages with the world.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Deleuze puts forward a conception of signs where the interpreter and their world are co-implicated.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Signs do not merely tell us about what they signify but directly impinge on thought, force thought into a constructive act of interpretation that changes the form that thought itself takes.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Guattari argues that meaning does not come from language itself, but rather from «very real social power formations».",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Guattari suggests that representation is the operative form that signification takes, and that it takes the form of a «snapshot» of «the totality of intensive reality» or «the totality of fluxes».",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Guattari refers to Peirce's assertion that algebraic equations are diagrams, suggesting that they function as signs «in place of the objects they relate to, independently of any effects of signification that may exist alongside them».",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Deleuze and Guattari strikingly speak of the diagram possibly resulting in «a patois of sensual delight, physical and semiotic systems in shreds, asubjective affects, signs without significance where syntax, semantics, and logic are in collapse».",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "The refrain produces a kind of internal cohesion, consisting in what Anne Sauvagnargues acutely describes as «the discordant set of diverse rhythms by which we configure ourselves».",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "To inhabit is to refuse any supremacy of the subject or Idea, to posit nature as the site of a vast and diverse set of processes of experimentation, to encounter and to express, to be implicated in the transitory, partial organisation of intensive signs: to take part in a semiorhythmology.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
