{
  "ADUs": {
    "1": {
      "text": "I propose in this text a rhythmic theory of signs drawn from the thought of Gilles Deleuze and Félix Guattari. I name this theory a semiorhythmology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "I suggest that the theory of rhythm developed in A Thousand Plateaus (1980) can be understood, in part, as the culmination of the diverse set of inquiries into signs that both Deleuze and Guattari undertook, individually and together, beginning in the 1960s.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "What could these two profound critics of representation have to say about the exemplary representational notion that is the sign?",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "For Michel Foucault representation is the key feature of the classical account of the sign",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "from Aristotle treating words as conventionally determined signs of affections of the soul through to Charles Sanders Peirce's account of signs as representations and Ludwig Wittgenstein's suggestion that signs may only be alive in their use, there seems to be little in the way of resources in the history of philosophy for detaching signs from a dependent role of representing something beyond themselves.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "Learning is not imitation but rather practical engagement, and teachers are not those who say «do as I do» but rather those who say «do with me».",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "To learn is «to constitute this space of an encounter with signs»; in other words, to open ourselves to a disorienting, alien outside, to immerse ourselves in a problem (such as the swimmer with the problem of the sea), to place the relations that constitute our bodies into relation with the relations that constitute the problem, and to give consistency to the new field this then constitutes.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "8": {
      "text": "The diagram allows this notion of rhythm to be detached from its phenomenological origin, and the movement of rhythm is no longer in the dynamic constitution of subject and world, but a movement only between milieus in permanent relation to chaos.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
